      "bodyTr": "Foreign visitor arrivals to South Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking the highest first-quarter figure on record. This represents a 23 percent increase compared to the same period last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed this growth to the global popularity of Korean culture. The BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Square last month is believed to have played a significant role in drawing visitors.\n\nThe phenomenon of Korean culture serving as a driving force for tourism has become increasingly evident in recent years. According to a 2024 survey by the Korean Culture and Tourism Institute, foreign tourists cited Korean Wave content as the top reason for their interest in visiting Korea, followed by traditional Korean culture in second place. Encouraging is the fact that this interest is expanding beyond Seoul to regional areas with diverse cultural heritage.\n\nAccording to Ministry of Culture data, foreign arrivals through provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent year-on-year. A substantial portion of tourists using regional airports subsequently turn their attention to regional sightseeing. The regional visitation rate among foreign visitors in the first quarter reached 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from the same period last year, while the duration of regional stays and credit card spending within regions jumped 36 percent and 27 percent respectively.\n\nWhile it may be premature to characterize this as a structural shift in the nature of foreign tourism to Korea, it is certainly encouraging that foreigners are increasingly venturing into regions, staying longer, and spending more. President Lee Jae-myung's mention at the State Affairs Council meeting on the 14th of coordinating regional residents, small business owners, and tourism activists while providing administrative support reflects the intention to nurture this trend.\n\nIn response, the Ministry of Interior and Safety has proposed forming public-private tourism councils at the city, county, and district levels, while the Ministry of Culture has expressed its commitment to supporting regional tourism activists. The direction of public-private cooperation to actively utilize private sector ideas is sound. However, for results to materialize, local administrative efficiency must support solutions addressing transportation, infrastructure, and regulatory issues, and political considerations that hamper effective decision-making must be excluded.\n\nTourism is currently one of the most promising solutions for addressing one of Korea's most pressing challenges: regional decline and the widening disparity between the capital region and non-capital areas. The opportunity created by the surge in foreign visitors driven by Korean culture must be properly seized.",
